>
  <article>
    <div class="article-header">
      <h1>Sanford Dispensary Guide</h1>
      <p class="subtitle">How to open a cannabis dispensary in Sanford, Maine</p>
    </div>

    <section class="fact-box">
      <h2>📋 Sanford at a Glance</h2>
      <table aria-label="Sanford dispensary requirements and market data" caption="Key requirements and market data for opening a dispensary in Sanford">
        <thead><tr><th scope="col">Requirement</th><th scope="col">Details</th></tr></thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>License Required</strong></td><td>Maine OCP Adult-Use Retail License</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Local Fee</strong></td><td>$2,000-2,500 annually</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>School Buffer</strong></td><td>500 ft minimum</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Commercial Rent</strong></td><td>$10-16/sq ft annually</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Current Dispensaries</strong></td><td>2-3 (opportunity)</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Why Sanford?</h2>
      <p>Sanford is the biggest city in York County that most people outside of Maine have never heard of. 21,000 residents, former mill town, geographically positioned between Portsmouth (New Hampshire) and Portland. It's not trendy or exciting, but it's strategically located — and the dispensary market reflects that. Sanford has 2-3 stores for 21,000 residents. Portland has 12+ for 68,000 residents. You do the math.</p>
      <p>The regional draw is real. Sanford sits at the intersection of I-95 and Route 109, positioned to capture customers from all of York County's underserved towns. Lebanon, Acton, Cornish, Parsonsfield — these are small towns with no dispensaries, and Sanford is the nearest option for many of them. There's also the New Hampshire factor: customers from southern New Hampshire (Dover, Rochester, Somersworth) cross the border into Maine for cannabis because New Hampshire's dispensary scene is more limited. Sanford is closer than Portland for these customers.</p>
      <p>The mill town history shows in the demographics. Sanford skews older and working-class compared to Portland. The customer base isn't the craft-concentrate demographic — it's people who want reliable flower, fair prices, and a straightforward experience. If you're planning a boutique premium positioning with artisanal extracts and rare strains, Sanford isn't your market. If you want to serve working-class Mainers and New Hampshire border crossers with solid products at fair prices, Sanford makes sense.</p>
    </section>

    <Callout title="The Honest Assessment" type="passion">
      Sanford won't make you famous. The ceiling is lower than Portland, the customer base is less affluent, and you won't have the variety-seeking connoisseurs. But the floor is solid, the rent is cheap, and there's room to grow before the market gets saturated.
    </Callout>

    <section>
      <h2>Market Data</h2>
      <table aria-label="Sanford market data">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Factor</th><th>Assessment</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>Population</td><td>21,000+</td></tr>
          <tr><td>York County Access</td><td>200,000+</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Competition</td><td>Low</td></tr>
          <tr><td>Access</td><td>I-95, Route 109</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The York County Catchment</h2>
      <p>York County has 200,000+ residents spread across small towns and mid-sized cities. Most of those towns don't have dispensaries and aren't going to get them soon — the population doesn't support standalone stores. Sanford, with its position on I-95 and Route 109, is where those customers come for cannabis. Right now, they're driving to Biddeford, Kittery, or Portland. When more licenses get issued, they'll come to Sanford — if there's a good store here.</p>
      <p>The underserved towns within driving distance of Sanford:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Lebanon:</strong> 6,000 residents, nothing closer than Sanford</li>
        <li><strong>Acton:</strong> 2,500 residents, geographically closer to Sanford than anyone else</li>
        <li><strong>Cornish, Parsonsfield:</strong> Tiny towns with no cannabis retail for miles</li>
        <li><strong>New Hampshire border towns:</strong> Dover, Rochester, Somersworth residents who cross into Maine for better prices and selection</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The delivery angle is significant here. If you operate in Sanford and offer delivery, you're not just competing with other Sanford stores — you're competing with "nothing" for customers in towns that have zero options. A delivery radius covering York County's underserved towns could add 20-30% to your customer base without opening additional locations.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The New Hampshire Factor</h2>
      <p>Maine's adult-use market has been legal since 2020. New Hampshire's market is more limited, with fewer dispensaries and higher prices. This makes Maine's border towns attractive to New Hampshire residents. Sanford is close enough to the border (about 15 miles from NH) that cross-border shopping is real.</p>
      <p>The NH customer is different from the Maine customer in some ways:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>They've been buying elsewhere:</strong> NH residents near the border have already established purchasing habits — often in Maine dispensaries. Your job is to give them a reason to switch or add Sanford as a regular stop.</li>
        <li><strong>They know what they want:</strong> Coming from NH's more limited market, they may not have seen the variety Maine offers. Good selection and competitive pricing can win them over.</li>
        <li><strong>They might be less price-sensitive:</strong> If they've been driving to Portland, stopping in Sanford saves them 20+ minutes. That convenience is worth something.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The NH factor also means your competitive set includes Portland and Kittery stores. NH customers who currently drive to Portland might switch to Sanford if it's closer and offers similar products. Track where your NH customers are coming from — if you see patterns, lean into that advantage.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Where to Set Up</h2>
      
      <h3>Main Street / Downtown Sanford</h3>
      <p>Downtown Sanford has character — older brick buildings, a renovated mill space or two, local businesses mixed with chains. It's not Portland, but it's not nothing. Main Street rent runs $14-16 per square foot. The customer here is local — Sanford residents who've been here for years, not passing tourists. They value consistency and familiarity. Your job is to become their store.</p>
      
      <h3>Route 109 / Highway Corridor</h3>
      <p>Route 109 heads toward the interstate and connects Sanford to I-95. This is where Sanford's newer commercial development is happening — strip malls, fast food, national retailers. Rent is $10-14 per square foot, lower than downtown. A dispensary here captures customers passing through and those coming from the highway. Visibility matters here more than foot traffic.</p>
      <p>The Route 109 customer is different from Main Street: they might be from out of town, passing through, or doing errands that happen to include a dispensary stop. If you're thinking about the regional draw from underserved York County towns, Route 109 is more convenient for those customers than downtown.</p>
      
      <h3>Alfred Road</h3>
      <p>Alfred Road is Sanford's other commercial corridor, quieter than Main Street but still active. Rent is $10-13 per square foot. This is where you go if you want cheap square footage and don't need high visibility. It's the budget option.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>The Competition</h2>
      <p>Two to three stores in Sanford doesn't tell the whole story. The competitive landscape includes:</p>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Portland:</strong> 12+ stores, 30 miles north. Some Sanford residents drive to Portland for selection, especially for products Sanford stores don't carry.</li>
        <li><strong>Kittery:</strong> Southern Maine's other hub, 20 miles south. Similar draw for NH border customers.</li>
        <li><strong>Biddeford:</strong> 12 miles north, 2-3 stores. Closer than Portland for the northern part of Sanford's customer base.</li>
      </ul>
      <p>The existing Sanford stores have early-entrant advantage and local loyalty. The store that's been there for three years has relationships. Competing on features alone is hard. Competing on convenience — better hours, better location, delivery — is more realistic.</p>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Best Locations</h2>
      <table aria-label="Sanford best dispensary locations by area" caption="Recommended commercial areas for dispensary locations in Sanford Maine with pros and rent estimates">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Area</th><th>Pros</th><th>Rent/Sq Ft</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td><strong>Main Street</strong></td><td>Downtown, regional traffic</td><td>$14-16</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Route 109</strong></td><td>Highway access, new development</td><td>$10-14</td></tr>
          <tr><td><strong>Alfred Road</strong></td><td>Commercial area</td><td>$10-13</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </section>

    <section>
      <h2>Key Takeaways</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>The opportunity:</strong> York County's largest city, 2-3 competitors, lowest rent in the Portland metro corridor. Room to establish before market gets crowded.</li>
        <li><strong>Regional draw:</strong> Serves all of York County's underserved towns plus NH border crossers. Delivery operation extends your reach significantly.</li>
        <li><strong>NH factor:</strong> 15 miles from NH border. Cross-border customers already buying in Maine. Closer than Portland for southern NH residents.</li>
        <li><strong>Customer profile:</strong> Working-class, price-conscious, reliable flower and fair prices over craft concentrates.</li>
        <li><strong>Location:</strong> Route 109 for highway visibility and regional draw. Main Street for local loyalty and character.</li>
      </ul>
    </section>

